== Records ==
The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}, entry for the 22nd year, 3rd month, 14th day of Emperor Ōjin's reign, states that Ani-hime, consort of the emperor, was allowed to return to Kibi. It also identifies her as the sister of Mitomowake, ancestor of the Kibi no Omi.{{Sfn|御友別（古代氏族）|2010年}}

On the 22nd year, 9th month, 6th day of Emperor Ōjin's reign, the emperor visited the Yoshita Ashimorimiya Palace (believed to be near {{ill|Ashimori, Okayama|ja|岡山市足守}}). During this visit, Mitomowake had his descendants serve as stewards. For this service, the emperor divided the Kibi Province among Mitomowake’s descendants as follows:{{Sfn|御友別（古代氏族）|2010年}}
* Eldest son, Inahayawake - Given Kawashima. Ancestor of the Shimotsudo no Omi. Kawashima later became Asakuchi District, Bitchū Province.
* Second son, Nakahiko - Given Kamitsudo. Ancestor of the Kamitsudo no Omi and Kaya no Omi. Kamitsudo later became Kamitsudo District, Bizen Province.
* Ototo-hiko - Given Mino. Ancestor of the Mino no Omi. Mino later became Mino District, Bizen Province.
* Younger brother, Kamowake - Given Natsukage. Ancestor of the Kasuga no Omi. The exact location of Natsukage is unknown, possibly near Kasukabe City.
* Elder brother, Urakobiwake - Given Sonokori. Ancestor of the Sonon no Omi. Sonokori later became Sonokori in Bitchū Province.
* Sister, Ani-hime - Received Orihime.

These descendants are noted to remain in Kibi Province.{{Sfn|御友別（古代氏族）|2010年}}

== Descendants ==
=== Individuals ===
The {{ill|Kuge Nenjū Gyōji|ja|公卿補任}} identifies {{ill|Kibi no Makibi|ja|吉備真備}} as a ninth-generation descendant of Mitomowake.{{Sfn|吉備御友別（国史）}}

Additionally, the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}}, entry for the 22nd day of the 10th month of Genkei 3 (879), records that Jinami of the Harima-based Innami no Omi clan was an 11th-generation descendant of Mitomowake. Jinami's lineage received the surname "Kasuga Ason."{{Sfn|吉備御友別（国史）}}

=== Clans ===
As stated, the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} describes Mitomowake as the ancestor of the Kibi no Omi.

In the {{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録}}, the following clan is noted as his descendants:
* Right Capital, Imperial Lineage, Kibi no Omi - Descendants of Mitomowake, grandson of Wakatakehiko.

== Interpretations ==
While the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} describes the division of Kibi under Mitomowake, some scholars suggest that these traditions were formulated as late as the 7th century, citing the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}} story of Emperor Nintoku and Kurohibime, daughter of the Kibi no Ama clan.{{Sfn|吉備御友別（国史）}}

Connections with the massive {{ill|Tsukuriyama Kofun (Okayama)|ja|造山古墳}} in Okayama City have also been examined.

